<dl id="n12137f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12137f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12137f"> 137(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pronated / supine</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">But, if compelled to sit upon benches or chairs, the chimpanzee attitude becomes at once converted into what Dr. Steen has called the &lsquo;Ancient Egyptian attitude.&rsquo; It is interesting to note that, as a rule, in the apes and in the dements, the arm arrangement, (as sometimes in the Egyptians statues) is one of rigid symmetry. Yet, when the Egyptian artists desired to convey the idea of Power or Intelligence, an asymmetrical disposition was featured that is seen to-day when a King is represented on a Throne <mark>holding a sceptre in a semi-pronated right hand and an orb in a fully supinated left hand</mark>. <small> F.G. Crookshank, <a name="MIOM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MIOM"><cite title="source">The Mongol in Our Midst</cite></a> (1924) 46-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
